nized or Americanized form of Polish, Czech, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian   Knap  , a surname of ultimately German origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Knappe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Klaus, Rainer, Siegfried, Wolf.","German: variant of   Knapp  ."]},{"name":"Knap","meanings":["Polish, Czech, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: of German origin (see   Knapp   1), meaning e.g. ‘pageboy, armor bearer’ (Czech), ‘weaver’ (Polish, Slovak, and Rusyn), ‘wool comber’ (Slovak and Slovenian), and ‘miner’ (Slovenian and Czech).","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Knapp   6."]},{"name":"Knabe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Gerhard, Helmut, Volker.","German: status name for a young man or a page, from Middle High German <i>knabe</i>. In aristocratic circles this term denoted a page or squire (a youth destined to become a knight), while among artisans it referred to a journeyman's assistant or (as a short form of <i>Lehrknabe</i>) ‘apprentice’. In the 15th century a semantic split between <i>Knabe</i> and its variants <i>Knape</i>, <i>Knapp(e)</i> resulted in <i>Knabe</i> meaning ‘boy’ and <i>Knapp(e)</i> ‘servant, apprentice’, and ‘miner’ in modern German."]},{"name":"Canup","meanings":["Americanized form of North German   Knapp   or   Knopp  ."]},{"name":"Knupp","meanings":["German: variant of   Knapp   or   Knopp  ."]},{"name":"Knibbs","meanings":["English: variant, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Knibb</b>, which may be related to   Knapp   or   Nobbs   or   Knipe  ."]},{"name":"Knapper","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>knap(p)er(e)</i>, an agent derivative of <i>knap(pe)</i> ‘knob, hillock’, for someone who lived by a hilltop or hillock; compare   Knapp  .","German (also <b>Knäpper</b>): habitational name for someone from either of two places in Westphalia named Knapp.","German (<b>Knäpper</b>): unflattering nickname from an agent derivative of <i>knappen</i> ‘to be 